-- Japan, Indonesia, Philippines, Thailand, Taiwan: Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-11-04T22:33:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-04/japan-indonesia-philippines-thailand-taiwan-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Bank of Japan will conclude a two-day policy meeting in
Tokyo, which was originally scheduled on Nov. 15 and 16.  Hiromasa Yonekura, chairman of Keidanren, Japan’s business
lobby, will hold a press conference at 11:30 a.m. in Tokyo.  The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation will begin a two-day
meeting of finance ministers in Kyoto.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic
and overseas securities during the week ended Oct. 29.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.925 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. A basis point is
0.01 percentage point.  The yen traded at 80.76 per dollar at 7:29 a.m. in Tokyo.  Indonesia: Gross domestic product increased 6.35 percent in
the third quarter from a year earlier, accelerating from a
revised 6.17 percent in the prior three months, according to the
median estimate of 13 economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 11 percent government note due November
2020 was 7.33 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market
Association. The rupiah was at 8,893.  Philippines: Consumer prices likely rose 3.3 percent in
October from a year earlier, after a 3.5 percent increase the
previous month, according to a Bloomberg News survey.  The central bank will also report foreign-exchange reserves
data for October. Reserves stood at a revised $53.8 billion in
September.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020
was 5.89 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange
Corp. The peso was at 42.505 per dollar.  Taiwan: The statistics bureau will say consumer prices rose
0.3 percent in October from a year earlier, after a 0.29 percent
gain the previous month, according to the median estimate of 11
economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The central bank will sell NT$100 billion ($3.3 billion) of
364-day non-deliverable certificates of deposits.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.27 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$30.59 per dollar.  Thailand: Foreign-exchange reserves data for the week ended
Oct. 29 is due today. The reserves rose 0.2 percent to $169.4
billion the previous week, according to central bank data.  The Bank of Thailand will sell 75 billion baht ($2.5
billion) of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.23
percent. The baht was at 29.70 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
